      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "The Innocence Project demonstrates a high level of organizational maturity and governance. With a <cite id=\"10\">board of 17 members</cite> that is <cite id=\"11\">100% independent</cite>, the charity ensures objective oversight of its mission. Their financial health is further underscored by a <cite id=\"12\">program expense ratio of 74.6%</cite>, which is well above industry standards for advocacy-based nonprofits. This efficiency allows a significant portion of donor funds to go directly toward <cite id=\"13\">post-conviction litigation and social work</cite> for exonerees."
      ],
      "summary": "The Innocence Project Inc is a leading national nonprofit dedicated to <cite id=\"1\">freeing innocent people who remain incarcerated</cite> and reforming the systems responsible for unjust imprisonment. Since its <cite id=\"2\">founding in 1992</cite>, the organization has pioneered the use of DNA testing to overturn wrongful convictions. In the 2023 fiscal year, the charity reported <cite id=\"3\">total revenue of $32,455,846</cite>, primarily driven by <cite id=\"4\">$26,644,804 in public contributions</cite>. Their work extends beyond individual litigation to include <cite id=\"5\">policy reform and strategic litigation</cite> aimed at preventing future injustices. The organization maintains an exceptionally strong financial position, evidenced by a <cite id=\"6\">perfect 100.0/100 from Charity Navigator</cite>. While their legal interventions are resource-intensive, they achieve systemic change by addressing the root causes of wrongful convictions, such as eyewitness misidentification and forensic science errors. For donors interested in criminal justice reform, the Innocence Project offers a proven track record of <cite id=\"7\">over 200 total exonerations</cite> achieved through rigorous legal and scientific advocacy.",
